document.title: Early Childhood Standards of Quality for Birth to Kindergarten

D4B9D3ED6BC44BB89971858E528FD23D.description: Point out that people need water to live, just like animals and plants.

29C24CC6A2714D02970AEE70785D83C2.description:
Sort photos of foods into a Venn diagram with categories such as “foods that
are grown in the ground,” “foods that come from animals,” and “both.”

009D800B078D408B857E15AE1F87A22D.description: Point out that yogurt is made from milk, which comes from a cow.

455CB1B59A704797B6C3F22596F0C1F7.description:
Ask a familiar adult if their snack or lunch contains something they are
allergic to.

6CA9EC9B30504C749792012082E7EBE1.description: Help a familiar adult measure and mix to prepare a fruit salad.

9B2F0E7EBF92433EA329672AFBB7E1C3.description: Sort food by food groups–fruit, vegetable, grain, protein, and dairy.

9DBB8C29F29140B791246FC7FDEE026C.description: Tell a familiar adult that drinking water is good for their bodies and brains.

BF041E43DF28459A9BCB2D645885338C.description: Remind a familiar adult that they can’t have pork sausages.

0171C2AECA644BF28EB096D86C9DBBB2.description:
Tell another child or familiar adult that they are allergic to (or “can’t have”)
peanuts.

878544CBEA414C06A03400D828D63EE9.description: Ask if a food is a fruit or vegetable.

9088E7EC1EE44D63BE2FA1996864C3F8.description:
After washing hands, help prepare snack by counting how many people are
eating and making sure there is enough for everyone.

77896CB1D9724D69B8B285FA6EE8DFE9.description: Tell another child that carrots are good for eyesight.

DE8ADF09569643C5A0843E6AC5182909.description:
Identify a variety of foods and livestock that typically come from farms/
ranches.

AAA95FB2AB4043A9A8EDF8A9150B0A71.description: Remind a familiar adult to also grab the ‘special’ milk for them.

BA6263339BA648D383536BE9C69436E6.description: Say, “I can’t eat strawberries because they make my belly feel yucky.”

4A0364F536214330A0CB2910495E457D.description: Help a familiar adult pass out cheese and crackers.

B71FAE890DCB49C9B15A1A5F94059E06.description: Separate play foods into “anytime foods” and “sometimes foods.”

4346EF6F6EC840999D369A891DFA6F8E.description:
Develop an awareness of how foods look, feel, taste, and smell different; how different foods affect
their bodies; and how foods are sorted into food groups.

FB089BE3FC4048E5A60D542B57AC34E0.description:
Ask another child about the unfamiliar food they are eating—what it tastes
like, what’s in it, etc.—most of the time.

DE9757C3D48E4904A3E5BF0B7DCD8205.description: Taste test different fruits they have not eaten before.

7A68843386684F769DAAA7A5DF1F8FBB.description: Sort scented markers in groups of smells they like or do not like.

CC53480AE98D42C2B9135BD022EEB2B4.description: Ask, “What’s that smell?” when lunch is delivered.

ACFF3A63D544415090BA42BDC506137F.description:
With modeling and support, ask another child about the unfamiliar food they
are eating—what it tastes like, what’s in it, etc.—sometimes.

03C82877C13D4C54B442B7E5D2749581.description: Try a new food after watching a familiar adult eat it.

9962CEA7BCBD4781B77BEFB424D6AB76.description:
With modeling and guidance, respond to other children eating unfamiliar
foods as a normal situation, most of the time.

C8F897B3016141FFB7F986D9FE1EE671.description:
Ask a familiar adult about what someone else is eating, when it is a food,
they aren’t familiar with.

419760C8EA5549E7ADDBE2D2F9BFC2E8.description: Sample a variety of apple types.

A029AF0661644F7FB7604389F3E7B494.description: Show interest in new or different tastes, smells, and foods.

B98849AC14274A5688DDF42A63F872C3.description: Ask for water with a meal.

6A7B19371A4B449A982E3287350ED275.description: Fill their own water bottle when it is empty.

1250B9CB057644E4AA731FB59051BA02.description: Get their own snack and sit down to eat it.

47CDDF3193BB4D869FDE8FFEE886CBDE.description: Tell a familiar adult that their belly is growling.

F287829842C74E31A8C95B10BFF57884.description: Say, “I’m full,” before throwing away the trash from their lunch.

EF3205C006FA4D018FC99F9D1B063DB0.description: Forget to drink water when busy with an activity.

7BDCED0E618A4A2F97D007A6F2EE3441.description: Drink independently from an open cup.

D80B4F7FE6694333AD71CC3F509A345A.description:
Make observations during an experiment with plants where one gets water,
and one doesn’t.

05E70984B02046D4B1E6C97FD4DE7492.description: Ask for their water cup to be refilled for a drink.

8ACF8B1AD73C4E2089CBB08144CA5401.description: Get their water bottle when they are thirsty.

2AE34542A62B4C1683CCAA1790BBF0E4.description: Become aware of and respond to feelings of thirst, hunger, and fullness.

7255DBD9EC864AD690D9816221207CF7.description: Children experience and become aware of the ways foods and drinks affect their bodies.

6B004248E73C447EA78CB647D454B6AD.description:
Use scissors to open a package of crackers instead of asking for adult
support.

7CE55E1062AD4CE5923E43C28F89B6B7.description:
Follow routines in the learning environment independently, such as putting
library books in a bin, making lunch choices, and hanging up their coat,
most of the time.

899B047A8F9D4ADB96CF3CE0442B89AE.description:
Count plates and cups to make sure there is enough for everyone to eat
snack.

18521E829DE340139B309403A860DAB2.description: Attempt to dress themselves for the weather before going outside.

D587B56922504A038F0C366D413DF06F.description: Ask for a bandage when they are bleeding.

40C9DC2FF82343989319FEBABE7FB288.description: Pass out cups to each child at snack time.

91D27203080F436AAB07620511A1057C.description: Drink independently from an open cup.

31ABD5E2E881403A82E206C183C25D91.description: Put things in their backpack to go home but forget to close it.

6ADE27BF4EDF41EB9CB3DDD3819FCC3B.description: Start using the bathroom without assistance.

383A24B4E5ED4CAC929956D6E364ABB5.description: Put the end of their zipper in but not yet pull it up.

4FFA09BDAAFD446486A7A0EABF568977.description: Show increasing ability to perform self-care routines and tasks.

21FE945B9F2248F39371DA29B5E89E1C.description: Explain to another child where to go during fire or tornado drills.

DDAAC91215E94B8FB9BDF02245418EC4.description: Identify areas of the playground that are off-limits for children.

F796F7147BC849E69E20B94509A56E28.description: Ask for help getting down if they are too high on a climber.

7ACB707748D542CDA0366D68F5F54DD9.description: Independently put on a bike helmet before getting on their bike.

17A7404E21194C0DBE11451E8E53C201.description:
Wait at a sidewalk intersection until the “WALK” signal lights up, then
look both ways before continuing.

72565426199B4ACF88EC15EFB47DFF27.description:
Tell other children to come to the door and line up when the fire alarm
goes off.

3840288B1B3E40BD9DC1CA158E3EB5B5.description:
Participate in a group discussion of how to be safe and give
examples such as walking when they are inside, respecting others’
bodies and personal space, and staying with their group.

C64AC66EFF324742B70D56273A67DB26.description: Walk with scissors held in a fist grasp.

9E6983F6C1994F4E8F21DA47A8E8FE22.description: Put their hands up to block a child from hitting them.

CC977F1F6328400C88221A3D966240D9.description: Say, “look both ways” before crossing the street with an adult.

172CB5DCE0B149638F39AA23F4D52549.description: Move away from a child who is kicking blocks over.

E2D51CE9DAC34B18B41836A16ACD4295.description: Move away from others at large group time so they have more space.

3211444BEA964A178AA0CA321E0C0798.description: With reminders, line up at the door as the fire alarm is going off.

BA5186871A2944869A5070CA5547B3FB.description: Demonstrate increasing awareness of safe boundaries and safety routines.

184261136FC4443BBE08DF86352E07E4.description:
Approach a familiar adult to announce that they are sick or “don’t feel good”
when they are coughing, have a runny nose, or feel feverish.

207CE8B5F60049DABF87D1D92498653C.description: Sing the alphabet song when they wash their hands.

4C831BF97FE84C62A2199EB2700C8849.description:
Follow handwashing routines independently and without prompting, most of
the time.

B173FFAB4C3B46E5A298DB82E651CCF2.description: Follow handwashing routines independently and without prompting, sometimes.

23C21476FBCD4059B95326D015CE35E5.description: Cough and sneeze into their elbow.

97730B92C48943F0AAA649C0DF004489.description: Tell someone not to touch them after seeing them lick their hand.

3486CA2852FB4F6D9768E3F37A005DA3.description: Get a tissue for another child with a runny nose.

F85509B457FA41AD8409C8B4EFA11A2B.description:
With prompting, wash their hands independently, before and after meals,
after toileting, and after outdoor times.

292BE429245446C488AC862FD9D3425C.description:
Tell a familiar adult they have a runny nose and need a tissue or, sometimes,
feel their nose running and grab a tissue on their own.

5C3BC0CC69134E0991D492CABC702328.description: With reminders, cough, and sneeze into their elbows

17BE07793155465B8BA1C13FDE4AF757.description:
Become aware of ways they can prevent the spread of germs and illnesses, and begin to identify
and manage some symptoms of illness.

0EE6E8AA47CB439FA3F8BC0DFFB73BA4.description:
Follow handwashing routines independently and without prompting, most of
the time.

6CE94DDB603A42F1AE779427869936FF.description:
Communicate why they are upset and brainstorm solutions with a familiar
adult.

60749C2BDBE24585A0FE3CB771D94FD4.description: Eat the healthy part of lunch first and save dessert for last.

7CF75F116C0F4685A769202CD5568E09.description:
Follow handwashing routines independently and without prompting,
sometimes.

05D55504AFF043FF9AEEEB7FABA499FB.description: Say, “I’m going to be tired!” after running around at recess.

A84E3D509993482A8C70A5C42E7E2C65.description: Ask a familiar adult, “Is this healthy for me?”

BDAA0A398E7D4D7789DBB14734DB617B.description:
With prompting, wash their hands independently, before and after meals,
after toileting, and after outdoor times.

7007C4D9F2F4421B98876316A0D63366.description: Run around the playground after having a disagreement with another child.

2B01EEB980D6430FA9B0F48773B74917.description: Pick up a box and announce, “I’m so strong!”

6CDA4D24025247B19CBFFB9A7EB654E1.description:
Begin to understand the connections between physical activity, hygiene, nutrition, emotional
wellness, and physical health.

DCC84497856F4D70BBAA9874343FF213.description:
Children recognize and practice the ways they can support and advocate for
their own needs and the safety of themselves and others.

F29FA152D2F149AEBD3D3847C720DD86.description: Color in a circle they have drawn.

6666A61961D84276B82056653FDEDDD3.description: Hit a ball with a paddle or a bat.

62D42D1688624BA2BFD5518604355E9D.description: Follow a magnetic maze with a magnet stick.

5D96EC9B1EA84AE5B02F5B97F4F0E7B7.description: Use child-safe tweezers to move pom-poms from one bowl to another.

F1CBC8D79DDD45C09501D844D0C49E61.description: Continue to use lacing cards with thinner string and more complex designs.

D4E7F17C5FCB40B3BE15BADAD71F9320.description: Use a mouse to control the cursor on a computer screen.

E7A99787EEA84EC592AFC12693BE87F0.description: Stacking small cubes in a tower.

88F7EE5C31144BEBB8F995F1D2ACA565.description: String smaller beads onto a pipe cleaner.

1D5BEC6B636A4BEE9F04FD39CAFCAAAC.description: String big wooden beads onto shoelaces or pipe cleaners.

CD3AE61B2EEE41FDA946BE3F21EEC227.description: Thread a shoelace or thick string through lacing cards.

88372C16A25A479CB7069876C3BD93D5.description: Place small pegs in a pegboard.

6962F2C38C2B426B9A2B34BBFB125117.description: Stretch rubber bands across a pegboard to make shapes.

451FBDE485614F9E96FBD56BF29B3A3D.description: Stretch small rubber bands around a tongue depressor several times.

AB4A074FE5B844AE9A12B40C7BE9E34A.description: Tighten nuts onto bolts with their fingers.

A2E14C9A2CA744B2951723C14601B156.description: Begin to zip their coat independently.

38D2B4579C024FFE99178CF5BE1F343B.description: Hold a pencil with full control.

0681EC83E76A44B8A67B6FF2D975A12A.description: Begin to follow a predefined path when cutting.

5E73FAD264D74381AA801A3B9F938BAB.description: Squeeze a hole puncher until it successfully punches a hole in paper.

89F14678D08947EF84CBDF3DC43B906B.description: Unzip their coat and finish zipping when someone else gets it started.

08D1FB67EC984EAE94BEFC3F3AE2B111.description: Use scissors to snip paper, and later cut in a line.

001723747F904FD0AFF789AE483066B7.description: Explore and develop more strength and precise control over their hands and fingers.

29F5525A923E413696C0262B7EB06F5A.description: “Blow” their nose independently (one nostril at a time).

1EDB12DFB71B45C99FE39E0A01F1D255.description: Wink, wiggle their ears, and other facial “tricks.”

322FB068AB2C4C3C877E29D80D910E33.description: Say more complex sounds (e.g., alveolar sounds – t, d, n).

6929A7F138B148A88196686B8B1A4473.description:
Say most sounds correctly. (l, s, r, v, z, ch, sh, and th may still be
challenging.)

A7E2933AD7F74B42BE65C6D9CF77A830.description:
Make different faces when a familiar adult asks them “What does mad/sad/
happy/etc. look like?”

69A74E798BD946DC851ABC350E85A4E1.description: Try to roll their tongue after seeing someone else do it.

98D1BFC622E84F0BB9DDF482C18A6ED2.description: “Blow” their nose when a familiar adult holds a tissue (both nostrils at once).

D46B0C0C13F14D8E8A5092A8D31AEF74.description:
Make happy, sad, angry, and surprised faces while looking at themselves in
a mirror.

3AED99DD201744F485480FA75666ADD9.description: Use a straw to blow a feather across the table.

701133E3AE864E319BA1892B1190FC0E.description: Explore and develop more precise control over the movements of their tongue and facial muscles.

A18F06C2AFB14D7EB4ADFB9D2C54A07B.description: Children explore and begin to develop skill in using their small muscles.

7B364F909DFB4EA7B59E448FAE9876E1.description: Balance while sitting on a yoga ball.

073E7C6ADC4641F88CF9BF1E051EB0AB.description: Run across the playground without falling.

64484BCA1FE74C9FB5903F0F907AA3F1.description: Climb on a short rock wall.

E6F4950D093E4EF59FFA37D40CCC20AD.description: Roll themselves up a ramp in their wheelchair.

8DACD4B16ACB4C78B0FE131C7957BBDC.description:
Use their large muscles for stationary and traveling movements, such as sitting upright, walking,
climbing, rolling a wheelchair or walker, etc.

7F6D7DF7F66341A39351EB42226E61B1.description: Skip with coordination and alternating foot and arm movements.

5B54BA270F194490AA5E2F03DA5C5EE3.description: Dribble a soccer ball with their feet.

2D4641FC125149DFBBEB804ECD192258.description: Tap a pattern with rhythm sticks.

952634F5BB334FB79705DE160A91FAA4.description: Follow the directions in a movement song.

3230E432D88E478DAEC05FE92721D4E1.description: Toss a ball to another child with more accuracy.

021CD9EE4B984B8ABDE6635CA855A508.description: Move through a simple obstacle course.

EFD21C0728154DAB887EA4D9679C2D20.description: Shake and turn a parachute to the directions in a song.

9E0F7CD90DB54B04A9D63FE27EBF579E.description: Practice kicking a ball into a net from varying distances.

E723F17162A146C7A28937BC04C22BDD.description:
Explore and develop more precise control over their large muscle movements, including moving
in rhythmic patterns as well as using their muscles to move objects in their environment with increasing
coordination.

EF32E85810494D98B307AABD2287BE8F.description: Move all the way across a set of monkey bars.

23B097B7ACA04B728C78981A54581A25.description:
Practice to increase the number of times they can dribble a basketball or
soccer ball.

D53CFF4EEC0E4B7C8D6D7D322F607B18.description: Measure the distance they jump and try to jump farther.

B4C096FE8D8A4A179E984A9C96DF2C32.description: Begin to move across the monkey bars.

AFD10FC00310413D9377E53476329B36.description: Throw a ball farther than before.

C29A42BA7A164F8890A03187C08DFCAD.description: Pedal a bike faster after using it every day during recess.

C81CEC63D9274A0D8EDADA865A554B55.description: Pedal a tricycle as fast as they can.

38B2301F72244443BE30507A2E6399FA.description: Climb on large motor equipment faster and with more confidence.

B2ADDB60B687408AAE74AC1D93A2E68C.description: Develop strength and stamina in their large muscles through repeated use.

3850CF6031A4412E8944F5500B834734.description: Children explore and begin to develop skill in using their large muscles.

C10F6B906B914E7CBEB07AE6FE0578C5.description: Ask a friend for help tying their shoes.

D126F9B49ED740BEB15C102E9135357E.description: High-five a classmate after racing them.

8EBE35BBC7694F90843401315F70C111.description: Show a classmate how to pedal a bike.

E2AE46174CF245C1B563EE3E4B7953EE.description: Help a classmate zip their coat.

AD18768B803E46B5837CB729BA96DBD1.description: Help a friend on the swing by pushing their back.

17BADBDBD1734075AA8B6C520E94A810.description: Work with another child to stack blocks into a tower.

8C04D3E6801043249483DBA65C374362.description: Help another child find their sleeve when putting on their coat.

C93CF68012D141589B30A1B3E9A399DB.description: Recognize and show respect for the varying physical skills and abilities of themselves and others.

ABC4EBB865904BA084B919FE57212BD3.description:
Develop their own challenges, such as putting bean bags on a balance
beam and avoiding the bean bags when crossing the balance beam.

45AF0EE72EAB4B8ABF19B641DE89B6E9.description:
Ask a familiar adult how long it takes to run around the playground and then
try to beat that time.

F58BF2967BD0409EA4F395902069EB5F.description: Ride a bike without training wheels.

478A606AABAD44FBABFB4518230C2F19.description: Try to climb monkey bars independently.

354166EE32FA45EAA64B8820E68DC2AE.description: Climb to a higher spot on a climbing wall.

3DA1B2C16C714BFF8495BC793DA84368.description: Ride a bike with training wheels.

0FB9C7D53FF44632BABEC3A940AC7D13.description: Ride a balance bike or scooter.

1F5559A330134A0F8A86C4DEF9C9E6B6.description: Try to walk the length of a balance beam or curb, over and over.

5BFAA59722804A3AB2AA4E0FC6C19E04.description: Explore and stretch the boundaries of their current physical abilities.

8377F3806B9E46F6A0F36092AF0E8E11.description: Copy dance moves from another person or from a video.

7A054083AED64F5C979E45F4B28CC1D3.description:
March in place while touching their right elbow to their left knee as it rises,
and their left elbow to their right knee when it comes up.

E6869ABE73454B4F85E1BE6583848CA6.description: Begin to show preference for a dominant hand (left/right handedness).

8D284E89E49F4D248DB8AACCFE619DFA.description: Reach across their body to pick up a crayon.

A178536BBBF04693A21FD55560B1573B.description:
Use both hands to touch their body parts during “Heads Shoulders Knees
and Toes.”

91ADD8BA1F3844D0BAA168F2B883AA23.description: Coordinate movements across and on both sides of the body.

161264342CC84DAEA099C6749C96AC1D.description: Move through an obstacle course, most of the time.

3701AD65C36F4319BBCB77970763E98E.description: Duck their head when walking under the slide.

F741889343FC4BBFBDDFE0CFC990DFF2.description:
Adjust their speed and strength when throwing a ball at targets that are
closer or farther away.

CBFE46064EFC4AA19AA52758306A6930.description: Dodge around other children when running, most of the time.

57004D9ED71A4C8486710CA51AD91892.description:
Explore how their bodies fit into different spaces, such as whether a tunnel
is too small for their shoulders to fit through or if their body will fit into a
cardboard box.

2D8C4DFD35F0448895B5B6DBE47A1B8C.description: Stretch out on the floor to compare their height to another child’s height.

8EA1524E866748559F446A030137F416.description: Toss or roll a ball to another child with increasing accuracy.

C98A799D789B457B90880458F918C7A1.description: Use distance vocabulary, such as near and far.

AE851E8CED0D4F249952D3F5B958D403.description: Move through a simple obstacle course without knocking things over.

B2BAB4C5ADD342DABAB4776C27CE2D1A.description: Notice that they have grown taller than a toy slide they used to play on.

38B1D03CF2C648DEBCAB82D689998E7C.description:
Explore and begin to perceive depth, distance, size, and the relationship between their own body
and the space around them.

CF126E40BC8943EF996CAC2F460AD363.description:
Demonstrates to a peer how to do the pinch and zoom gestures with their
finger and thumb on an iPad.

4E9FA552D16C48D9AC422A0C05B8D4F4.description: Use the correct body parts when dancing to “The Hokey Pokey.”

848FC08B3CF34215AFFDEF3677420AEE.description:
Hold up the correct number of fingers when a familiar adult says, “Show me
5 fingers!”

2B2EB8CA8A894133B3612F183F9F384E.description: Wrap a pipe cleaner around their finger to make it spiral.

F11E6FDA4FA64CFAA66DF2FD6CA11CB2.description: Identify their pinky finger while giving a “pinky promise.”

28F4FC599F844204A36464AAF9E5ACF6.description:
Point to the correct body parts when dancing to “Head Shoulders Knees and
Toes.”

B19BB5BDAFA441D596FCB055C2BB8A46.description: Use their head and elbows while playing soccer.

FBB03C08C7334B7399089E6063FEFB35.description: Use their foot to open a garbage can with a foot lever.

B25ADD35D80F4CCEA923BE6BBE070BF0.description: Recognize parts of the human body and how their body helps them engage with their environment.

72123AFDD3E143A0B91C0A275A116990.description:
Participate in a group activity to create a book with lists and/or illustrations of
ways they used each of their senses that day.

C3FAC703200947188A4A5071157680BB.description:
Describe and sort foods based on their senses, such as sorting foods by
color or by texture.

34AD852E1FDF491AA52BD61797A4BF27.description:
Close their eyes and identify different animal noises being played through a
speaker.

DED53D264CCD4EB29632C729710CB971.description: Taste different foods and decide if they like them or not.

3C8D32671CE9441C879EC337E78DD2DD.description: Smell food being delivered for lunch and say, “That smells like chicken!”

3EC252B0116E4715B787AD527020CA1F.description: Identify smells (like spices or familiar smells) from smelling jars.

9F040C3BF464437EB39AF7ABA85E5E5C.description: Feel a bump on their arm and tell a familiar adult it is itchy.

4CC64BFAD7534B01A0392FF9D01FCB3D.description: Take a drink of milk and recognize that it tastes bad and tell a familiar adult.

D1E8C9A3FB234019836D1B72F4B2F792.description: Smell smoke from a bonfire outside and tell a familiar adult about it.

CFE528E142D44FBFA014DD3227FB9698.description:
Use their senses (hearing, vision, taste, touch, smell) and their voices to perceive and respond to
the world around them.

1449867885FD4557BC5221886B63D3A3.description: Children begin to understand their bodies and how they function.
